<span id="freeTextContainer7332641987191569032">Written in letter form. Though the story revolves around serious subject matters for a young woman of the time -- preserving her virtue, future marriage prospects, inequality, employer/male v. employee/female power struggles -- the story is not without humor. Reading this book was not a class assignment: I chose to read it on my own. It may be a little more gauche and not as refined as Jane Austen would write it, but I appreciated Richardson&apos;s brutal honesty and 18th century view of hypergamy. </span>
  <span id="freeText7332641987191569032" style="display:none">Written in letter form. Though the story revolves around serious subject matters for a young woman of the time -- preserving her virtue, future marriage prospects, inequality, employer/male v. employee/female power struggles -- the story is not without humor. Reading this book was not a class assignment: I chose to read it on my own. It may be a little more gauche and not as refined as Jane Austen would write it, but I appreciated Richardson's brutal honesty and 18th century view of hypergamy. </span>
